   "source": [
    "Confusion Matrix — Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "A confusion matrix is a table used to evaluate the performance of a classification model by comparing the actual values with the predicted values.\n",
    "\n",
    "It shows how many predictions were:\n",
    "\n",
    "correct\n",
    "\n",
    "incorrect\n",
    "\n",
    "and breaks them into four categories:\n",
    "\n",
    "True Positive (TP)\n",
    "\n",
    "True Negative (TN)\n",
    "\n",
    "False Positive (FP)\n",
    "\n",
    "False Negative (FN)\n",
    "\n",
    "It is called a confusion matrix because it helps us understand where the model is getting confused between classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Simple Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "A confusion matrix is a table that tells us:\n",
    "\n",
    "how many positive cases were predicted correctly\n",
    "\n",
    "how many negative cases were predicted correctly\n",
    "\n",
    "how many wrong positive predictions were made\n",
    "\n",
    "how many wrong negative predictions were made\n",
    "\n",
    "Standard Structure of a Confusion Matrix\n",
    "                    Predicted\n",
    "                Positive   Negative\n",
    "Actual Positive     TP         FN\n",
    "Actual Negative     FP         TN\n",
    "Meaning of Each Term\n",
    "1. True Positive (TP)\n",
    "\n",
    "Model predicted Positive, and actual is also Positive.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "A patient has disease, and the model correctly predicts disease.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. True Negative (TN)\n",
    "\n",
    "Model predicted Negative, and actual is also Negative.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "A patient is healthy, and the model correctly predicts no disease.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. False Positive (FP)\n",
    "\n",
    "Model predicted Positive, but actual is Negative.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "A healthy patient is wrongly predicted as diseased.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is also called a Type I Error.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. False Negative (FN)\n",
    "\n",
    "Model predicted Negative, but actual is Positive.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "A diseased patient is wrongly predicted as healthy.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is also called a Type II Error.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example of Confusion Matrix in Disease Detection\n",
    "Actual / Predicted\tPositive\tNegative\n",
    "Positive\tTP\tFN\n",
    "Negative\tFP\tTN\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose:\n",
    "\n",
    "40 sick patients correctly predicted as sick → TP = 40\n",
    "\n",
    "50 healthy patients correctly predicted as healthy → TN = 50\n",
    "\n",
    "5 healthy patients wrongly predicted as sick → FP = 5\n",
    "\n",
    "10 sick patients wrongly predicted as healthy → FN = 10\n",
    "\n",
    "Then the confusion matrix becomes:\n",
    "\n",
    "Actual / Predicted\tPositive\tNegative\n",
    "Positive\t40\t10\n",
    "Negative\t5\t50\n",
    "Why Confusion Matrix is Important\n",
    "\n",
    "A confusion matrix is important because accuracy alone is not enough, especially when data is imbalanced.\n",
    "\n",
    "It helps us understand:\n",
    "\n",
    "what kind of mistakes the model is making\n",
    "\n",
    "whether the model is missing positives\n",
    "\n",
    "whether the model is generating too many false alarms\n",
    "\n",
    "For example:\n",
    "in disease detection, false negatives may be more dangerous.\n",
    "in spam detection, false positives may be more harmful.\n",
    "\n",
    "So confusion matrix gives a much deeper understanding than just one metric.\n",
    "\n",
    "Interview Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "A confusion matrix is a performance evaluation table for classification models that compares actual and predicted classes. It summarizes predictions into four outcomes: true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negative. It is useful for understanding model errors and for calculating metrics like accuracy, precision, recall, specificity, and F1-score.\n",
    "\n",
    "Beginner-Friendly Version\n",
    "\n",
    "Think of confusion matrix as a report card for a classification model.\n",
    "\n",
    "It shows:\n",
    "\n",
    "where the model was right\n",
    "\n",
    "where the model was wrong\n",
    "\n",
    "what type of wrong prediction happened\n",
    "\n",
    "One-Line Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "A confusion matrix is a table that compares actual and predicted classifications and shows TP, TN, FP, and FN."
   ]
